10813nam a22013455i 9783110245837DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20102010gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)859566452  a97831102458377 a10.1515/97831102458372doi  a(DE-B1597)57624  a(OCoLC)687690325  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP51 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aFostering Language Teaching Efficiency through Cognitive Linguistics /ced. by Sabine De Knop, Antoon De Rycker, Frank Boers. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (388 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aApplications of Cognitive Linguistics [ACL] ,x1861-4078 ;v1700tFrontmatter -- tTable of contents -- tFostering language teaching efficiency through cognitive linguistics: Introduction -- tPart I – The importance of usage-based language acquisition, but why it may not suffice in contexts of second language learning -- tLanguage in the mind -- tPhrasal verbs in EFL course books -- tBasic-level salience in second language vocabulary acquisition -- tDoes 'chunking' foster chunk-uptake? -- tPart II – How Cognitive Linguistics can inform decisions about what to teach -- tHaving many meanings: A corpus study of Spanish EFL writers' construals with have -- tSeven events in three languages: Culture-specific conceptualizations and their implications for FLT -- tCanonicity and variation in idiomatic expressions: Evidence from business press headlines -- tThe use of metaphor and metonymy in academic and professional discourse and their challenges for learners and teachers of English -- tArgument constructions and language processing: Evidence from a priming Experiment and pedagogical implications -- tChoosing motivated chunks for teaching -- tPart III – How Cognitive Lingusics can inform decisions about how to teach -- tFostering the acquisition of English prepositions by Japanese learners with networks and prototypes -- tA prototype approach to auxiliary selection in the Italian passato prossimo -- tObstacles to CM-guided L2 idiom interpretation -- tCorpus-informed integration of metaphor in materials for the business English classroom -- tImproving word learn-ability with lexical decomposition strategies -- tCognitive theory as a tool for teaching pronunciation -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn contexts of instructed second language acquisition there is a need for teaching methods that are optimally efficient, i.e. teaching interventions that generate a maximal return on learners' and teachers' investment of time and effort. In the past couple of decades, many researchers have argued that insights from Cognitive Linguistics (CL) - when suitably translated for pedagogical purposes - can make a major contribution to fostering such language teaching efficiency. This collective volume assesses and supplements those CL proposals. The first part of the book positions CL-inspired language pedagogy vis-à-vis recent trends in mainstream applied linguistics and illustrates through several case studies that language-focused instruction (including CL-inspired instruction) is a useful - if not indispensable - complement to learner-autonomous, incidental acquisition. The second part demonstrates how CL research can help pedagogues identify hitherto neglected language elements that merit explicit targeting in second language instruction. The third part consists of contributions that put the pedagogical efficiency of several CL-inspired interventions to the test in classroom experiments. Additions to the currently available armoury of teaching methods are proposed. The kinds of target language items under examination in the book range from single words over multiword units to grammar patterns. Throughout, the volume illustrates how much pedagogy-oriented Cognitive Linguistics has matured in recent years.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aFremdsprachenlernen. 4aKognitive Linguistik. 4aSprachunterricht. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCognitive Linguistics.  aLanguage Teaching.1 aAlejo, Rafael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAttardo, Salvatore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnden, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoers, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoers, Frank, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBunce, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Phyllis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCho, Kanako, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Knop, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Knop, Sabine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDe Rycker, Antoon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Rycker, Antoon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDeconinck, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEddington, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEyckmans, June, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFong, Yu-Ying, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFraser, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamrick, Phillip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrera, Honesto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators